[3] USA: Cruise liner banned from Caribbean ports
USA: Cruise ship carrying Texas Ebola nurse refused entry in Belize
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
17 Oct 2014: (WP) A Texas health-care worker who "may have" handled lab specimens from Ebola victim Thomas Eric Duncan has been isolated in a cabin on board a commercial cruise ship in the Caribbean, according to U.S. Department of State. And Belize Coast Guard won't let the vessel or any of its thousands of passengers into port.... -- more
[Byline: Lindsey Bever & Fred Barbash]
http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/10/17/cruise-ship-carrying-texas-ebola-nurse-refused-entry-in-belize

[The U.S. government is working to get her and her husband back home (see next report below). This shows a complete misunderstanding of the mechanics of transmission -- unless health authorities now believe (without any evidence) that asymptomatic (symptomless) contacts who are not coughing or sneezing can spread the virus. The viral load is so low in asymptomatic cases that it is only likely to spread on skin or mucous membrane contact -- and then to immunize rather than sicken. See also comment in next report below. - Mod.JW]

--
Mexico fails to grant access to cruise ship carrying Texas health worker
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
USA, 17 Oct 2014: (WP) Updated and corrected. The cruise ship carrying a Texas health-care worker who "may have" handled lab specimens from Dallas Ebola victim Thomas Eric Duncan is headed back to the United States after Mexican authorities failed to grant permission for the ship to dock off the coast of Cozumel, according to a Carnival spokeswoman.

The Carnival Magic had been waiting off the Mexican coast since Fri 17 Oct 2014] morning for its scheduled port visit. Mexican authorities still hadn't given clearance by noon, so the ship continued to its home port of Galveston, Texas, where it was due back on Sun [19 Oct 2013], according to Carnival.

The health worker, a lab supervisor who has not been named, has shown no symptoms of the disease but remains on board and in voluntary isolation, according to Carnival. "We greatly regret that this situation, which was completely beyond our control, precluded the ship from making its scheduled visit to Cozumel and the resulting disappointment it has caused our guests," read a statement from Carnival.

The Texas Health Presbyterian Hospital employee and a partner boarded the ship 12 Oct 2014 in Galveston before the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention updated the requirement for active monitoring, the U.S. State Department said in a statement. Although the worker is healthy, the U.S. government had said it was working with the cruise line to get the ship back to America "out of an abundance of caution."
The employee did not come into direct contact with Duncan, the 1st Ebola patient diagnosed in the United States. However, she may have been exposed to his clinical specimens, the State Department said.

Carnival said it would provide USD200 credits to guests aboard the ship and 50 percent discounts on a future cruise..... -- more
[Byline: Lindsey Bever, Fred Barbash & Elahe Izadi]
http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/10/17/cruise-ship-carrying-texas-ebola-nurse-refused-entry-in-belize

[Huge financial implications for the cruise lines -- let alone lost tourist income for the unvisited ports. Will all the thousands of passengers (capacity 3700), captain and crew (1367) then have to be monitored? The ship's next cruise cancelled? I would not be surprised to hear that half the passengers for that cruise have already cancelled, although there is no danger on board. I would snap up half-price tickets for their next cruise like a shot -- but will its cruise ports still ban it? 'Deep decontamination' will take weeks. - Mod. JW]

